u820a\u7cbe\u9078||WARNER||\n|-\n|Sept 2003||\u300a\u60c5\u76e1\u591c\u4e0a\u6d77\u56de\u61b6\u9304\u300b ||GODOT THEATRE  ||\u3010\u60c5\u76e1\u591c\u4e0a\u6d77\u3011\u96cb\u6c38\u8001\u6b4c\u6b4c\u821e\u5287 \n|-\n|Feb 2004||\u300aBest of The Best\u300b ||WARNER ||\n|-\n|March 2004||\u300a\u6292\u7434\u6642\u9593\u300b ||WARNER ||\n|-\n|July 2004||\u300aUnder The Moon Light 2004\u300b ||\u5ee3\u5dde\u5929\u85dd ||\n|-\n|May 2005||\u300a\u4e00\u5343\u500b\u6625\u5929\u300b\u3010\u7d93\u5178\u5fa9\u523b\u7248\u3011|| music543.com||\n|-\n|April 2007||\u300a\u4e0d\u4e86\u60c52007\u7d93\u5178\u6b4c\u66f2\u9999\u6e2f\u6f14\u5531\u6703\u300b ||UNIVERSAL ||\n|-\n|Oct 2007||\u8521\u7434\u300a\u91d1\u8072\u6f14\u594f\u5ef3\u300b||UNIVERSAL ||\n|-\n|November 2008||\u4e0d\u6094 ||UNIVERSAL||\n|-\n|August 2009||\u611b\u50cf\u4e00\u9996\u6b4c||UNIVERSAL ||\n|-\n|April 2010||\u5982\u5922\u4ee4|| \u64ce\u5929\u5a1b\u6a02||\n|-\n|August 2013||\u5168\u65b0\u98db\u7fd4 ||[[Sony Music]] ||\n|-\n|Oct 2014||Reunion\uff08OT\uff1a[[:fr:\u00c7a va pas changer le monde|\u00c7a va pas changer le monde]]\uff09||Sony Music ||\n|}\n\n==In popular culture==\nTsai's song \"Forgotten Times\" (\u300a\u88ab\u907a\u5fd8\u7684\u6642\u5149\u300b) features prominently in the 2002 hit Hong Kong film ''[[Infernal Affairs]]'' as a recurring element of its storyline, and also in its sequels. As well as serving to elucidate the theme of the films, the song plays an important plot function in chronologically connecting various elements of the story.<ref>{{cite web|title=Taiwan Music Legend Tsai Chin|url=http://womenen.redcome.com/html/report/76105-1.htm|publisher=Women's Foreign Language Publications of China|accessdate=6 May 2012|author=CRI|date=22 February 2006}}<!-- note: being archived at archive.org --></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tsai Chin}}\n* {{in lang|zh}} \n\n{{Golden Melody Awards for Best Mandarin Female Singer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Taiwanese singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Taiwanese singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Kaohsiung]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese female singers]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese film actresses]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese Mandopop singers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Kaohsiung]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n\n\n{{Taiwan-singer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: \uff09 \u2192 ), \uff08 \u2192 (, \uff1a \u2192 :", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tsai_Chin_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "In the Pines (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = In The Pines\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Triffids]]\n| cover      = In The Pines.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = August 1986\n| recorded   = April 14\u201318, 1986\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[folk rock]]}}\n| length     = 34:28 / Reissue 55:40\n| label      = Mushroom\n| producer   = [[Bruce Callaway]] / [[David McComb]]\n| prev_title = [[Born Sandy Devotional]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[Calenture (album)|Calenture]]\n| next_year  = 1987\n}}\n\n'''''In The Pines''''' is an album by [[The Triffids]], released in August 1986, which reached No. 69 on the Australian Album Charts.<ref name=\"Kent\">{{cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]]|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W.|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}} Note: Used for Australian Singles and Albums charting from 1970 until [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] created their own [[ARIA Charts|charts]] in mid-1988.</ref>\n\n==Recording==\nThe album was produced by [[Bruce Callaway]] and [[David McComb]],<ref name=\"Holmgren\">{{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20020728092009/http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/t/triffids.html | url = http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/t/triffids.html | title = The Triffids | last1 = Holmgren | first1 = Magnus | last2 = Skjefte | first2 = Morten | first3 = Stefan | last3 = Warnqvist | first4 = Vince | last4 = Simonetti | work = Passagen.se | publisher = [[Australian Rock Database]] (Magnus Holmgren) | archivedate = 28 July 2002 | accessdate = 18 May 2014 }}</ref> recorded in a woolshed on a remote Western Australian farming property, owned by the McCombs' parents, on an eight-track machine for a grand total of $1190 (the album notes that $340 of this was spent on alcohol (beer, wine and vodka), which exceeded the $310 spent on food, the $300 on recording equipment hire and the $240 on petrol.\n\n<blockquote>\"It was just an idea that had been kicking around for some time. We had some time to do it and it was something that didn\u2019t involve a huge effort to do. If it didn\u2019t work, it didn\u2019t work. It didn\u2019t matter. It was something of a holiday really. At the very least we would have had a chance to play the songs and if it didn't work out have demoed some songs for the next album. It was just something that we did and which turned out to be releasable.\" - Graham Lee </blockquote>\n\nMacDonald later noted, \"Dave had the idea for a long time of doing something in a very basic setting, with very basic equipment. Like ''[[The Basement Tapes]]'' or''[[ Music From Big Pink]]'', where by transplanting yourself to this unique location it creates a special sound. As far as the rest of us were concerned, it wouldn't have mattered if we continued recording in London or Sydney.\"<ref>{{cite web| work= [[Rock's Backpages]] | title=The Triffids: Album By Album|author=Andrew Mueller | url=https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/the-triffids-album-by-album}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2010, David McComb's parents still owned the property. His ashes has been scattered there, in the pine grove.\n\n==Reissue==\nThe reissue by Domino Records released in February 2007 included three additional songs that had previously been held over for ''[[Calenture (Album)|Calenture]]'':  \"Trick Of The Light\", \"Blinder By The Hour\" and \"Jerdacuttup Man\". It also included two other songs that were not on the original edition: \"She's Sure The Girl I Love\" and \"Wish to See No More\".  The previous version of \"Born Sandy Devotional\" is expanded. The reissue was remixed by Bruce Callaway, the sound engineer of the original recordings.\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score ={{Rating|4.5|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r205414|pure_url=yes}} link]\n}}\n[[AllMusic]] said, \"The stripped-down, communal feel of this record beautifully captures the essence of the Triffids' folk- and country-influenced rock and underscores frontman David McComb's musical and lyrical talent for translating the isolated mental and physical landscapes of western Australia.\"<ref>{{cite web| work= Allmusic | title=In The Pines|author=Wilson Neate| url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/in-the-pines-mw0000456904}}</ref>\n\n[[Mat Snow]] claimed it was, \"probably the best Australian country and western album ever made, though the competition can hardly be called stiff.\"<ref>{{cite web| work= [[Rock's Backpages]] | title=The Triffids|author=Mat Snow | url=https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/the-triffids}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll songs written by David McComb, unless otherwise noted.<ref name=\"APRA\">[http://www.apra.com.au/site/public/searchworksresult.stm Australasian Performing Rights Association] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124161012/http://www.apra.com.au/site/public/searchworksresult.stm |date=2008-01-24 }}</ref>\n\n=== Original edition ===\n\n# \"Suntrapper\" - 2:18 \n# \"In the Pines\" - 2:35\n# \"Kathy Knows\" - 3:45\n# \"25 To 5\" - 1:06\n# \"Do You Want Me Near You?\" (Allan MacDonald<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 3:41\n# \"[[Once a Day]]\" (Bill Anderson<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 4:01 \n# \"Just Might Fade Away\" - 2:59 \n# \"Better Off This Way\" - 2:51 \n# \"Only One Life\" - 1:30\n# \"Keep Your Eyes on the Hole\" - 2:14\n# \"One Soul Less on Your Fiery List\" - 4:18 \n# \"Born Sandy Devotional (Edit)\" - 1:28 \n# \"Love and Affection\" - 1:42\n\n=== Remastered edition ===\n\n# \"Suntrapper\" - 2:34 \n# \"In the Pines\" - 2:41 \n# \"Kathy Knows\" - 4:01 \n# \"25 to 5\" - 1:06 \n# \"Only One Life\" - 1:39 \n# \"Do You Want Me Near You?\" (Allan MacDonald<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 3:32 \n# \"Trick of the Light\" (David McComb, Graham Lee<ref name=\"APRA\" />)- 3:59 \n# \"Once a Day\" (Bill Anderson<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 4:09 \n# \"She's Sure The Girl I Love\" (Barry Mann, Cynthia Weil<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 2:24 \n# \"Jerdacuttup Man\" (David McComb, James Paterson<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 4:51 \n# \"Just Might Fade Away\" - 3:10 \n# \"Better off This Way\" - 2:59 \n# \"Keep Your Eyes on the Hole\" - 2:21 \n# \"Blinder by The Hour\" - 2:59 \n# \"Wish to See No More\" - 2:41 \n# \"One Soul Less on Your Fiery List\" - 4:42 \n# \"Born Sandy Devotional\" - 3:54 \n# \"Love and Affection\" - 1:58\n\n==Personnel==\nCredited to:<ref name=\"Holmgren\"/>\n* [[David McComb]] - [[Singing|vocals]], [[guitar]], mandolin\n* [[Graham Lee (Australian musician)|'Evil' Graham Lee]] - acoustic guitar, pedal and lap steel guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Martyn Casey]] - [[bass guitar]]\n* [[Jill Birt]] - vocals, keyboards\n* [[Robert McComb]] - [[violin]], guitar, drums (\"Do You Want Me Near You?), harmonica, mandolin, [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n* [[Alsy MacDonald]] - [[Drum kit|drums]], backing vocals\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120205182322/http://www.furious.com/perfect/triffids.html A Retrospective with Graham Lee and Rob McComb by Wilson Neate]\n\n{{The Triffids}}\n\n[[Category:1986 albums]]\n[[Category:Domino Recording Company albums]]\n[[Category:The Triffids albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = In The Pines\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Triffids]]\n| cover      = In The Pines.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = August 1986\n| recorded   = April 14\u201318, 1986\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[folk rock]]}}\n| length     = 34:28 / Reissue 55:40\n| label      = Mushroom\n| producer   = [[Bruce Callaway]] / [[David McComb]]\n| prev_title = [[Born Sandy Devotional]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[Calenture (album)|Calenture]]\n| next_year  = 1987\n}}\n\n'''''In The Pines''''' is an album by [[The Triffids]], released in August 1986, which reached No. 69 on the Australian Album Charts.<ref name=\"Kent\">{{cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]]|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W.|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}} Note: Used for Australian Singles and Albums charting from 1970 until [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] created their own [[ARIA Charts|charts]] in mid-1988.</ref>\n\n==Recording==\nThe album was produced by [[Bruce Callaway]] and [[David McComb]],<ref name=\"Holmgren\">{{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20020728092009/http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/t/triffids.html | url = http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/t/triffids.html | title = The Triffids | last1 = Holmgren | first1 = Magnus | last2 = Skjefte | first2 = Morten | first3 = Stefan | last3 = Warnqvist | first4 = Vince | last4 = Simonetti | work = Passagen.se | publisher = [[Australian Rock Database]] (Magnus Holmgren) | archivedate = 28 July 2002 | accessdate = 18 May 2014 }}</ref> recorded in a woolshed on a remote Western Australian farming property, owned by the McCombs' parents, on an eight-track machine for a grand total of $1190 (the album notes that $340 of this was spent on alcohol (beer, wine and vodka), superseding the bill for food of $310 and also the $300 for recording equipment hire and $240 for petrol.\n\n<blockquote>\"It was just an idea that had been kicking around for some time. We had some time to do it and it was something that didn\u2019t involve a huge effort to do. If it didn\u2019t work, it didn\u2019t work. It didn\u2019t matter. It was something of a holiday really. At the very least we would have had a chance to play the songs and if it didn't work out have demoed some songs for the next album. It was just something that we did and which turned out to be releasable.\" - Graham Lee </blockquote>\n\nMacDonald later noted, \"Dave had the idea for a long time of doing something in a very basic setting, with very basic equipment. Like ''[[The Basement Tapes]]'' or''[[ Music From Big Pink]]'', where by transplanting yourself to this unique location it creates a special sound. As far as the rest of us were concerned, it wouldn't have mattered if we continued recording in London or Sydney.\"<ref>{{cite web| work= [[Rock's Backpages]] | title=The Triffids: Album By Album|author=Andrew Mueller | url=https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/the-triffids-album-by-album}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2010, David McComb's parents still owned the property. His ashes has been scattered there, in the pine grove.\n\n==Reissue==\nThe reissue by Domino Records released in February 2007 included three additional songs that had previously been held over for ''[[Calenture (Album)|Calenture]]'':  \"Trick Of The Light\", \"Blinder By The Hour\" and \"Jerdacuttup Man\". It also included two other songs that were not on the original edition: \"She's Sure The Girl I Love\" and \"Wish to See No More\".  The previous version of \"Born Sandy Devotional\" is expanded. The reissue was remixed by Bruce Callaway, the sound engineer of the original recordings.\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score ={{Rating|4.5|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r205414|pure_url=yes}} link]\n}}\n[[AllMusic]] said, \"The stripped-down, communal feel of this record beautifully captures the essence of the Triffids' folk- and country-influenced rock and underscores frontman David McComb's musical and lyrical talent for translating the isolated mental and physical landscapes of western Australia.\"<ref>{{cite web| work= Allmusic | title=In The Pines|author=Wilson Neate| url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/in-the-pines-mw0000456904}}</ref>\n\n[[Mat Snow]] claimed it was, \"probably the best Australian country and western album ever made, though the competition can hardly be called stiff.\"<ref>{{cite web| work= [[Rock's Backpages]] | title=The Triffids|author=Mat Snow | url=https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/the-triffids}}{{subscription required|s}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll songs written by David McComb, unless otherwise noted.<ref name=\"APRA\">[http://www.apra.com.au/site/public/searchworksresult.stm Australasian Performing Rights Association] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124161012/http://www.apra.com.au/site/public/searchworksresult.stm |date=2008-01-24 }}</ref>\n\n=== Original edition ===\n\n# \"Suntrapper\" - 2:18 \n# \"In the Pines\" - 2:35\n# \"Kathy Knows\" - 3:45\n# \"25 To 5\" - 1:06\n# \"Do You Want Me Near You?\" (Allan MacDonald<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 3:41\n# \"[[Once a Day]]\" (Bill Anderson<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 4:01 \n# \"Just Might Fade Away\" - 2:59 \n# \"Better Off This Way\" - 2:51 \n# \"Only One Life\" - 1:30\n# \"Keep Your Eyes on the Hole\" - 2:14\n# \"One Soul Less on Your Fiery List\" - 4:18 \n# \"Born Sandy Devotional (Edit)\" - 1:28 \n# \"Love and Affection\" - 1:42\n\n=== Remastered edition ===\n\n# \"Suntrapper\" - 2:34 \n# \"In the Pines\" - 2:41 \n# \"Kathy Knows\" - 4:01 \n# \"25 to 5\" - 1:06 \n# \"Only One Life\" - 1:39 \n# \"Do You Want Me Near You?\" (Allan MacDonald<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 3:32 \n# \"Trick of the Light\" (David McComb, Graham Lee<ref name=\"APRA\" />)- 3:59 \n# \"Once a Day\" (Bill Anderson<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 4:09 \n# \"She's Sure The Girl I Love\" (Barry Mann, Cynthia Weil<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 2:24 \n# \"Jerdacuttup Man\" (David McComb, James Paterson<ref name=\"APRA\" />) - 4:51 \n# \"Just Might Fade Away\" - 3:10 \n# \"Better off This Way\" - 2:59 \n# \"Keep Your Eyes on the Hole\" - 2:21 \n# \"Blinder by The Hour\" - 2:59 \n# \"Wish to See No More\" - 2:41 \n# \"One Soul Less on Your Fiery List\" - 4:42 \n# \"Born Sandy Devotional\" - 3:54 \n# \"Love and Affection\" - 1:58\n\n==Personnel==\nCredited to:<ref name=\"Holmgren\"/>\n* [[David McComb]] - [[Singing|vocals]], [[guitar]], mandolin\n* [[Graham Lee (Australian musician)|'Evil' Graham Lee]] - acoustic guitar, pedal and lap steel guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Martyn Casey]] - [[bass guitar]]\n* [[Jill Birt]] - vocals, keyboards\n* [[Robert McComb]] - [[violin]], guitar, drums (\"Do You Want Me Near You?), harmonica, mandolin, [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n* [[Alsy MacDonald]] - [[Drum kit|drums]], backing vocals\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120205182322/http://www.furious.com/perfect/triffids.html A Retrospective with Graham Lee and Rob McComb by Wilson Neate]\n\n{{The Triffids}}\n\n[[Category:1986 albums]]\n[[Category:Domino Recording Company albums]]\n[[Category:The Triffids albums]]\n", "name_user": "Freewheeling frankie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecording:Improved the wording of the sentence about the money spent recording the album.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_the_Pines_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Fruitvale Bridge", "text_new": "{{Infobox bridge\n| name                = Fruitvale Bridge\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = Fruitvale Avenue vertical-lift railroad bridge. connecting Oakland & Alameda, CA, USA.jpg\n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = View of a vertical lift bridge spanning the estuary separating Oakland from Alameda.\n| caption             = Fruitvale Avenue vertical-lift railroad bridge. The Fruitvale Avenue Miller-Sweeney bridge is directly behind the raised span of the railroad bridge.\n| coordinates         = \n| os_grid_reference   = \n| carries             = railroad\n| crosses             = [[Oakland Estuary]]\n| locale              = [[San Francisco Bay Area]]\n| official_name       = \n| other_name          = \n| named_for           = \n| owner               = \n| maint               = \n| heritage            = \n| id                  = \n| id_type             = \n| website             = \n| preceded            = \n| followed            = \n| design              = [[Vertical-lift bridge]]\n| material            = steel\n| material1           = \n| material2           = \n| length              =\n| width               =\n| height              = {{convert|175|ft|abbr=on}}\n| depth               = \n| traversable         = \n| towpath             = \n| mainspan            = \n| number_spans        = \n| piers_in_water      = \n| load                = \n| clearance_above     =\n| clearance_below     = {{convert|65|ft|abbr=on}} (raised)\n| lanes               = \n| life                = \n| num_track           = \n| track_gauge         = \n| structure_gauge     = \n| electrification     = \n| architect           = \n| designer            = \n| contracted_designer = \n| winner              = \n| engineering         = \n| builder             = \n| fabricator          = \n| begin               = \n| complete            = \n| cost                = \n| open                = \n| inaugurated         = \n| rebuilt             = \n| collapsed           = \n| closed              = 2000\n| replaces            = \n| replaced_by         = \n| traffic             = \n| toll                = \n| map_type            = United States Oakland#San Francisco Bay Area#California\n| map_relief          = \n| map_dot_label       = \n| map_image           = \n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| name                = Fruitvale Avenue Bridge\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = ABL railroad bridge with Fruitvale Avenue Bridge's bascule span partially raised in background.jpg\n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = View of a bascule bridge (drawbridge) spanning the estuary separating Oakland from Alameda.\n| caption             = Partially raised bascule on road bridge, immediately behind rail bridge.\n| coordinates         =\n| os_grid_reference   = \n| carries             = cars and trucks on Fruitvale (Oakland) and Tilden Avenues (Alameda)\n| official_name       = Miller-Sweeney Bridge\n| other_name          = \n| named_for           = \n| owner               = \n| maint               = \n| heritage            = \n| id                  = \n| id_type             = \n| website             = \n| preceded            = \n| followed            = \n| design              = Single leaf [[bascule bridge]]\n| material            = steel, concrete\n| material1           = \n| material2           = \n| length              = {{convert|215|ft|abbr=on}}\n| width               = {{convert|52|ft|abbr=on}} roadway<br/>{{convert|6|ft|1|in|abbr=on}} sidewalks\n| height              = \n| depth               = \n| traversable         = \n| towpath             = \n| mainspan            = \n| number_spans        = \n| piers_in_water      = \n| load                = \n| clearance_above     =\n| clearance_below     = {{convert|15|ft|abbr=on}} (high tide)<br/>{{convert|21|ft|abbr=on}} (low tide)\n| lanes               = 4\n| life                = \n| num_track           = \n| track_gauge         = \n| structure_gauge     = \n| electrification     = \n| architect           = \n| designer            = McCreary-Koretsky International\n| contracted_designer = \n| winner              = \n| engineering         = \n| builder             = Hensel Phelps\n| fabricator          = Kaiser Steel\n| begin               = \n| complete            = \n| cost                = \n| open                = \n| inaugurated         = \n| rebuilt             = \n| collapsed           = \n| closed              = \n| replaces            = \n| replaced_by         = \n| traffic             = 15,300\n| toll                = \n}}\n\nThe '''Fruitvale Bridge''' and the '''Fruitvale Avenue Bridge''' (the latter officially the '''Miller-Sweeney Bridge at Fruitvale Avenue''') are parallel bridges that cross the [[Oakland Estuary]], linking the cities of [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] and [[Alameda, California|Alameda]] in California. The Fruitvale Bridge is a vertical-lift railroad [[moveable bridge]], while the Fruitvale Avenue Bridge is a road [[bascule bridge]] that connects Fruitvale Avenue in Oakland with Tilden Avenue in Alameda.\n\n==Rail bridge==\nThe rail bridge is immediately west of the Miller-Sweeney road bridge. The rail bridge connected Fruitvale Avenue in Oakland with Tilden Way in Alameda. It has been out of service since 2000.\n\n===History===\nThis [[lift bridge]] was constructed in 1951 to replace an earlier bridge that originally served the [[East Bay Electric Lines|SP interurban trains]] from [[San Francisco]] (SP's Interurban Electric Railway discontinued service in 1941). From 1951 until September 11, 1996, the [[Southern Pacific Railroad]] operated freight service across the bridge to serve shippers in Alameda and to connect with the [[Alameda Belt Line]] railroad. After SP was acquired by [[Union Pacific]] on September 11, 1996, UP provided infrequent service to Alameda until service was discontinued in 2000.\n\n===Design===\nThe right-of-way still exists through the [[East Bay (San Francisco Bay Area)|East Bay]], however, the tracks on both sides of the bridge have been severed and the span remains raised at 65 feet above water level, except when operated for maintenance and testing.  The bridge is owned by the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]] and is operated by the [[Alameda County, California|County of Alameda]].  The Miller-Sweeney bridge tender, a county employee, operates the railroad bridge from controls in the Miller-Sweeney [[bridge tender's house|control house]].  The last train across the bridge ran in 2000.\n\n==Road bridge==\nThe road bridge is officially named the '''Miller-Sweeney Bridge at Fruitvale Avenue'''.<ref name=ACPWA>{{cite web |url=https://www.acpwa.org/pas/miller-sweeny-bridge |title=Miller-Sweeny ''[sic]'' Bridge |author= |date= |publisher=Alameda County Public Works Agency |accessdate=3 May 2017}}</ref> It has no overhead steel structure like the other road bridges between Alameda and Oakland (the [[High Street Bridge]] and the [[Park Street Bridge]]) so tall vehicles should use the Miller-Sweeney Bridge.<ref name=ACPWA /> Miller-Sweeney opens approximately 1,600 times per year to accommodate marine traffic.<ref name=ACPWA />\n\n===History===\nA bridge at this location initially opened in 1894, initially carrying rail traffic.<ref name=ACPWA /> It was regraded to accommodate road traffic, and the train tracks were removed in 1951 with the completion of the dedicated vertical-lift rail bridge.<ref name=ACPWA /> The present Miller-Sweeney Bridge was completed in 1973 by the US Army Corps of Engineers and turned over to Alameda County in 1975.<ref name=ACPWA /> Miller-Sweeney won a prize bridge award for movable spans from the [[American Institute of Steel Construction]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aisc.org/globalassets/nsba/prize-bridge-brochures/1974prizebridgebrochure.pdf |title=Prize Bridges 1974 |author= |date=1974 |pages=16\u201317 |publisher=American Institute of Steel Construction |accessdate=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Miller-Sweeney Bridge was damaged in the [[1989 Loma Prieta earthquake]] and was damaged again in 1991 when a fully loaded barge hit the span.<ref name=ACPWA />\n\n===Design===\nThe Miller-Sweeney Bridge is normally opened by two {{convert|75|hp|adj=on}} motors, which take 66 seconds to fully open the bridge to 79\u00b0.<ref name=ACPWA /> The motors typically operate in tandem, drawing electricity from [[Alameda Municipal Power]]. Under emergency conditions, a portable generator may be used to power the single backup {{convert|5|hp|adj=on}} motor, which takes 20 minutes to fully open the bridge.<ref name=ACPWA />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Fruitvale Bridge (Alameda Belt Line)}}\n{{Commons category|Fruitvale Avenue Bridge}}\n* {{gnis|2350986|Fruitvale Bridge}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://modelrailroading.wordpress.com/2009/08/29/the-fruitvale-avenue-railroad-bridge-of-alameda-calif/ |title=The Fruitvale Avenue Railroad Bridge of Alameda, Calif. |author=Callan, Miles |date=29 August 2009 |website=Interacting with Miniature Railroading |accessdate=3 May 2017}}\n\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure = Crossings\n|place = [[Oakland Estuary]]\n|bridge = Fruitvale Bridge\n|upstream text = South\n|upstream = [[High Street Bridge]]\n|downstream text = North\n|downstream = [[Park Street Bridge]]\n}}\n\n{{San Francisco Bay watershed}}\n{{Alameda, California}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges in Alameda County, California]]\n[[Category:Railroad bridges in California]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Alameda, California]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Oakland, California]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Vertical lift bridges in California]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Bay Trail]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1951]]\n[[Category:1951 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox bridge\n| name                = Fruitvale Bridge\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = Fruitvale Avenue vertical-lift railroad bridge. connecting Oakland & Alameda, CA, USA.jpg\n| image_upright       = \n| alt                 = View of a vertical lift bridge spanning the estuary separating Oakland from Alameda.\n| caption             = Fruitvale Avenue vertical-lift railroad bridge. The Fruitvale Avenue Miller-Sweeney bridge is directly behind the raised span of the railroad bridge.\n| coordinates         = \n| os_grid_reference   = \n| carries             = railroad\n| crosses             = [[Oakland Estuary]]\n| locale              = [[San Francisco Bay Area]]\n| official_name       = \n| other_name          = \n| named_for           = \n| owner               = \n| maint               = \n| heritage            = \n| id                  = \n| id_type             = \n| website             = \n| preceded            = \n| followed            = \n| design              = [[Vertical-lift bridge]]\n| material            = steel\n| material1           = \n| material2           = \n| length              =\n| width               =\n| height              = {{convert|175|ft|abbr=on}}\n| depth               = \n| traversable         = \n| towpath             = \n| mainspan            = \n| number_spans        = \n| piers_in_water      = \n| load                = \n| clearance_above     =\n| clearance_below     = {{convert|65|ft|abbr=on}} (raised)\n| lanes               = \n| life                = \n| num_track           = \n| track_gauge         = \n| structure_gauge     = \n| electrification     = \n| architect           = \n| designer            = \n| contracted_designer = \n| winner              = \n| engineering         = \n| builder             = \n| fabricator          = \n| begin               = \n| complete            = \n| cost      