{"title_page": "Immigrant investor programs", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Golden passport|the book|The Golden Passport{{!}}''The Golden Passport''|text=Not to be confused with [[Golden Age Passport]].}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n'''Immigrant investor programs''' are programs designed to attract [[foreign capital]] and businesspeople by providing the right of residence and citizenship in return. These are also known as '''citizenship by investment''', '''golden visa''', or '''golden passport''' programs.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Cosmopolites: The Coming of the Global Citizen|last=Abrahamian|first=Atossa Araxia|publisher=Columbia Global Reports|year=|isbn=978-0-9909763-6-3|location=|pages=70\u201393|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-03-11/passport-king-christian-kalin-helps-nations-sell-citizenship|title=The Passport King|last=Clenfield|first=Jason|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://skift.com/2015/03/12/the-man-who-helps-countries-turn-investments-into-passports-for-the-rich/|title=The Man Who Helps Countries Turn Investments into Passports for the Rich|date=12 March 2015|website=Skift|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> \n\nImmigrant investor programs usually have multiple criteria that must be fulfilled for the investment to qualify, often pertaining to job creation, purchasing of real estate, non-refundable contributions or specific targeted industries.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Global Residence and Citizenship Handbook|last=Kalin|first=Christian H.|publisher=Ideos Publications|year=2015|isbn=978-0992781859|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Most of these programs are structured to ensure that the investment contributes to the welfare, advancement and economic development of the country in which they wish to reside or belong to. It is more often more about making an economic contribution than just an investment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biznews.com/undictated/2016/06/30/how-to-get-a-second-passport-citizenship-by-investment-is-booming/|title=How to get a second passport: \"Citizenship by investment\" is booming |date=30 June 2016|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nA [[golden visa]] is a [[permanent residency]] visa issued to individuals who invest, often through the purchase of property, a certain sum of money into the issuing country.\n\nThe roots of golden visas have been traced back to the 1980s when [[tax haven]]s in the Pacific and Caribbean began \"cash-for-passport\" programs that facilitated visa-free travel and provided tax advantages.{{sfn|Shachar|Baub\u00f6ck|Bloemraad|Vink|2017|p=794}} For example, in 1984, [[St Kitts and Nevis]] began its program which offered not only permanent residency but [[citizenship]] to foreign nations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Houlder|first=Vanessa|date=29 June 2016|title=Citizenship is for sale to the wealthy, Malta is among states to offer second passports, easing access to the wider EU|url=https://www.ft.com/content/155936ec-2728-11e6-8ba3-cdd781d02d89|work=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\nNowadays, golden visas generally refer to investor programs that allow individuals to obtain residency through investments while Investor programs that lead to citizenship are called citizenship by investment programs.\n\nThe issuing of golden visas expanded dramatically during the 21st century with around 25% of all countries issuing such visas as of 2015.<ref>IMF Working Paper, WP/15/93, Too Much of a Good Thing?:    Prudent Management of Inflows \nunder Economic Citizenship Programs, by Xin Xu, Ahmed El-Ashram and Judith Gold https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/wp/2015/wp1593.pdf</ref> Statistics on the issuing of golden visas is scarce but the IMF estimated in 2015 that the vast majority of golden visas are issued to Chinese nationals.<ref>IMF Working Paper, WP/15/93, Too Much of a Good Thing?:    Prudent Management of Inflows \nunder Economic Citizenship Programs,    by Xin Xu, Ahmed El-Ashram and Judith Gold https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/wp/2015/wp1593.pdf</ref>\n\n==Requirements and issuing==\nGolden visas require investments of anywhere from \u20ac250,000 in Greece up to \u00a32,000,000 in the U.K. The most common method for obtaining a golden visa is through the purchase of real estate with a minimum value.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rodriguez|first=Cecilia|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ceciliarodriguez/2013/09/29/want-to-live-in-europe-buy-a-residency-permit/ |title=Want To Live in Europe? \"Buy\" A Residency Permit |website=Forbes|date=29 September 2013|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> Golden visas have been especially popular with Chinese nationals, over 100,000 of whom acquired them during the period from 2007 to 2016.<ref>{{cite news|author=CBS/AP|date=12 May 2017|title=Chinese investors spent $24B on \"golden visas\" in U.S. and elsewhere|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/golden-visas-chinese-investors-24-billion-in-u-s-and-elsewhere/|publisher=CBS News}}</ref>\n\n[[Portugal Golden Visa|Portugal's golden visa]] was introduced during the [[Great Recession]] to help attract investment into the country's housing market. By 2016 the country had issued 2,788 golden visas of which 80% had gone to Chinese nationals.<ref name=\"Almeida\">{{cite news|last=Almeida|first=Henrique|date=20 January 2016|title=Chinese Stuck in Portugal's Visa Limbo|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-20/chinese-property-buyers-stuck-in-portugal-s-golden-visa-limbo|work=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nWhile golden visas allow High Net Worth Individuals to obtain residency by investment, Citizenship By Investment Programs allow investors to become naturalised citizens and obtain a passport.\n\nA number of Caribbean countries have citizenship by investment programs including Dominica, St. Lucia, Grenada, Antigua & Barbuda and Saint Kitts & Nevis.\n\nEuropean countries such as Malta, Turkey and Cyprus also offer citizenship by investment programs to individuals that the minimum investment requirements outlined in their citizenship law.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gittleson|first=Kim|date=4 June 2014|title=Where is the cheapest place to buy citizenship?|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-27674135|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe worlds most popular residency by investment program Malaysia MM2H visa received a total of 7904 main applicants in 2019. While Turkey the worlds most popular citizenship by investment program received a total of 2611 main applicants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imidaily.com/data/|title=Investment Migration Insider Data Center|last=Insider|first=Investment Migration|website=Investment Migration Insider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nThe issuing of so-called \"golden visas\" has sparked controversy in several countries. A lack of demonstrable economic benefits and security concerns have been among the most common criticisms of golden visas. In 2014 the Canadian government suspended their golden visa program. But because of the [[Canada\u2013Qu\u00e9bec Accord relating to Immigration and Temporary Admission of Aliens]] that allows Quebec to maintain its own immigration policy, Quebec maintains its own golden visa program.<ref>{{cite news|last=Yan|first=Sophia|date=25 March 2014|title=Canada kills investor visa popular with Chinese|url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/02/12/news/canada-chinese-immigration/index.html|publisher=CNN}}</ref> The golden visas have been criticized by members of the European Parliament for disfavoring the concept of citizenship<ref>{{cite news|date=22 November 2014|title=Buying their way in|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21633854-schemes-effect-sell-visas-rich-foreigners-come-under-fire-buying-their-way|work=The Economist}}</ref> and in 2014 the [[European Parliament]] approved a [[non-binding resolution]] that an EU passport should not have a \"price tag.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Vi\u00f1a|first=Gonzalo|date=8 April 2016|title=Malta's golden passport scheme draws fresh criticism|url=https://www.ft.com/content/6f98892e-fbf3-11e5-b3f6-11d5706b613b|work=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a study, the EU has won approximately \u20ac25bn over the last 10 years through foreign direct investment programs.<ref>{{cite news|date=24 January 2019|title=Golden visa\u2019 schemes deserve tougher scrutiny|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b6589fdc-1f0b-11e9-b126-46fc3ad87c65|work=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\n== By country ==\nAccording to ''Corpocrat Magazine'' in 2016, the countries with the top-ranked immigrant investor programs in the world were [[Malta]], [[Cyprus]], [[Portugal]], [[Austria]], the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada, [[Antigua and Barbuda]], [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]], Spain, [[Latvia]], [[Monaco]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Ukraine]], [[Grenada]], [[Abkhazia]], [[Saint Lucia]], Australia, Hong Kong, Singapore, UAE and [[Dominica]].\n\nSaint Kitts & Nevis has issued more passports through its Citizenship By Investment Program than any other country, as of 2018 the total number of passports stood at 16,544. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imidaily.com/data/|title=Investment Migration Insider Data Center|last=Insider|first=Investment Migration|website=Investment Migration Insider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://corpocrat.com/2015/10/20/25-immigrant-investor-citizenship-programs-in-the-world/|title=25+ Great Investor Visas in the World \u2013 Corpocrat Magazine|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> However, citizenship by investment applicants represent only a small proportion of new passports. In 2016, 994,800 citizenship applicants were granted across the EU, according to Eurostat, with just 0.1 percent of applications made under investment schemes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9a6eb914-9e23-11e8-85da-eeb7a9ce36e4|title=EU prepares crackdown on \u2018citizenships for sale\u2019|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Dominican passport|Dominica]] implemented [[Dominica citizenship by investment programme|its program]] in 1993 to provide investors the opportunity to gain Dominican citizenship via a contribution to its Economic Diversification Fund or the purchase of an alternatively approved project along with a fee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ciu.govt.kn/st-kitts-nevis-old/citizenship/|title=Citizenship {{!}} Government of St. Kitts & Nevis \u2013 Citizenship By Investment Program|website=www.ciu.govt.kn|access-date=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maltese passport|Malta Individual Investor Programme]],<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://iip.gov.mt/|title=Individual Investor Programme  \u2013 Malta|website=iip.gov.mt|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> which [[Henley & Partners]] was contracted in 2014 by the [[Government of Malta]] to design and implement, is similarly capped at 1,800 applicants. Applicants are subject to a thorough due diligence process which guarantees that only reputable applicants acquire Maltese citizenship. Moreover, applications from countries where international sanctions apply may not be accepted. Applications from a particular country can also be excluded on the basis of a Government policy decision.<ref name=\":1\" /> The minimum investment for this program is $870,000 with a non-refundable contribution of $700,000.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{anchor|Quebec}}\nThe Quebec Immigrant Investor Program is a Canadian program which allows investors who intend to settle in the province of [[Quebec]] to invest money in Canada. The [[Government of Quebec|Quebec government]] said it would accept a maximum of 1,750 applications to the Immigrant Investor Program during the period of 5 to 20 January 2015. Applicants with an intermediate-advanced aptitude in French are not subject to the cap and may apply at any time. The program has been associated with the lack of [[affordable housing in Canada|housing affordability]] in [[Vancouver]].<ref>http://www.richmond-news.com/news/foreign-sales-peak-in-richmond-as-quebec-ramps-up-investor-immigrant-program-1.2300630</ref>\n\nThe United States [[EB-5 visa]] program requires overseas applicants to invest a minimum of anywhere from $500,000 to $1&nbsp;million, depending on the location of the project, and requires at least 10 jobs to be either created or preserved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uscis.gov/eb-5|title=EB-5 Immigrant Investor Program|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> When these criteria are met, the applicant and their family become eligible for a [[Permanent residence (United States)|green card]]. There is an annual cap of 10,000 applications under the EB-5 program.{{cn|date=January 2020}} The US Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) has offered its EB-5 Immigrant Investor Program since 1990. It is designed to encourage foreign investment in infrastructure projects in the US, particularly in Targeted Employment Areas (TEA), high unemployment areas. The funds are channeled through agencies called regional centers, now designated only by the US Department of Homeland Security. The funding opportunities allow the investor to make a sound financial investment and obtain a US \u201cGreen Card.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Riley |first1=Kim |title=New federal rulemaking makes major changes to EB-5 Immigrant Investor Program |url=https://transportationtodaynews.com/news/14728-new-federal-rulemaking-makes-major-changes-to-eb-5-immigrant-investor-program/ |website=Transportation Today |publisher=Macallan Communications |location=Washington DC |date=26 July 2019}}</ref> One of the more successful examples of the program is Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission's program through the Delaware Valley Regional Center to raise over $200&nbsp;million for completion of a major project on the Pennsylvania Turnpike.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Welitzkin |first1=Paul |title=Chinese investors helping build major US road link |url=http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/us/2014-12/02/content_19013341.htm |work=China Daily (USA) |agency=New Media |date=2 December 2014 |location=New York NY}}</ref>\n\nA large majority of users of such programs are wealthy Chinese seeking legal security and a better quality of life outside of their home country. More than three-quarters of the applicants to Canada's (since canceled) immigrant investor program were Chinese.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaelcole/2014/02/13/canada-slams-door-on-45k-chinese-millionaires-with-end-of-visa-program/|title=Canada Slams Door on 45K Chinese Millionaires With End of Visa Program|last=Cole|first=Michael|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> Money laundering scandals involving banks in Malta and Latvia have made citizenship schemes more contentious by drawing attention to the lack of controls on Russian funds entering EU countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/4f0fb6c4-5f78-11e8-ad91-e01af256df68|title=Malta bank was set up with \u2018criminal proceeds\u2019, say prosecutors|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe UK grants investor visas. As per the official statistics with the [[British Home Office]], as many as 255 Golden Visas were granted in the first half of 2019 alone.<ref>Y-Axis, [https://www.y-axis.com/news/wealthy-people-investing-golden-visa-uk-increasing/ Wealthy people investing in The Golden Visa of the UK increasing] </ref> {{as of|March 2020}}, an individual can apply for the UK Tier 1 (Investor) visa if they wish to invest an amount of \u00a32 million or more in the UK. The applicant must be from outside Switzerland and the European Economic Area to apply for such a visa, along with various other eligibility requirements. With this class of visa, a person can go to the UK for a maximum duration of 3 years and 4 months, with the ability to apply for an extension of 2 more years. The visa holder can apply to settle after 5 years or less; the greater the investment, the shorter the waiting period.<ref name=ukiv>{{cite web | title=Investor visa (Tier 1) | website=GOV.UK | date=7 February 2014 | url=https://www.gov.uk/tier-1-investor | access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Economic citizenship]]\n* [[EB-5 visa]]\n* [[Immigration tariff]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Immigration]]\n[[Category:Foreign direct investment]]\n[[Category:Residency]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Golden passport|the book|The Golden Passport{{!}}''The Golden Passport''|text=Not to be confused with [[Golden Age Passport]].}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n'''Immigrant investor programs''' are programs designed to attract [[foreign capital]] and businesspeople by providing the right of residence and citizenship in return. These are also known as '''citizenship by investment''', '''golden visa''', or '''golden passport''' programs.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Cosmopolites: The Coming of the Global Citizen|last=Abrahamian|first=Atossa Araxia|publisher=Columbia Global Reports|year=|isbn=978-0-9909763-6-3|location=|pages=70\u201393|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-03-11/passport-king-christian-kalin-helps-nations-sell-citizenship|title=The Passport King|last=Clenfield|first=Jason|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://skift.com/2015/03/12/the-man-who-helps-countries-turn-investments-into-passports-for-the-rich/|title=The Man Who Helps Countries Turn Investments into Passports for the Rich|date=12 March 2015|website=Skift|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> \n\nImmigrant investor programs usually have multiple criteria that must be fulfilled for the investment to qualify, often pertaining to job creation, purchasing of real estate, non-refundable contributions or specific targeted industries.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Global Residence and Citizenship Handbook|last=Kalin|first=Christian H.|publisher=Ideos Publications|year=2015|isbn=978-0992781859|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Most of these programs are structured to ensure that the investment contributes to the welfare, advancement and economic development of the country in which they wish to reside or belong to. It is more often more about making an economic contribution than just an investment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biznews.com/undictated/2016/06/30/how-to-get-a-second-passport-citizenship-by-investment-is-booming/|title=How to get a second passport: \"Citizenship by investment\" is booming |date=30 June 2016|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nA [[golden visa]] is a [[permanent residency]] visa issued to individuals who invest, often through the purchase of property, a certain sum of money into the issuing country.\n\nThe roots of golden visas have been traced back to the 1980s when [[tax haven]]s in the Pacific and Caribbean began \"cash-for-passport\" programs that facilitated visa-free travel and provided tax advantages.{{sfn|Shachar|Baub\u00f6ck|Bloemraad|Vink|2017|p=794}} For example, in 1984, [[St Kitts and Nevis]] began its program which offered not only permanent residency but [[citizenship]] to foreign nations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Houlder|first=Vanessa|date=29 June 2016|title=Citizenship is for sale to the wealthy, Malta is among states to offer second passports, easing access to the wider EU|url=https://www.ft.com/content/155936ec-2728-11e6-8ba3-cdd781d02d89|work=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\nThe issuing of golden visas expanded dramatically during the 21st century with around 25% of all countries issuing such visas as of 2015.<ref>IMF Working Paper, WP/15/93, Too Much of a Good Thing?:    Prudent Management of Inflows \nunder Economic Citizenship Programs, by Xin Xu, Ahmed El-Ashram and Judith Gold https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/wp/2015/wp1593.pdf</ref> Statistics on the issuing of golden visas is scarce but the IMF estimated in 2015 that the vast majority of golden visas are issued to Chinese nationals.<ref>IMF Working Paper, WP/15/93, Too Much of a Good Thing?:    Prudent Management of Inflows \nunder Economic Citizenship Programs,    by Xin Xu, Ahmed El-Ashram and Judith Gold https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/wp/2015/wp1593.pdf</ref>\n\n==Requirements and issuing==\nGolden visas require investments of anywhere from $100,000 in [[Dominica]] up to \u00a32,000,000 in the U.K. The most common method for obtaining a golden visa is through the purchase of real estate with a minimum value.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rodriguez|first=Cecilia|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ceciliarodriguez/2013/09/29/want-to-live-in-europe-buy-a-residency-permit/ |title=Want To Live in Europe? \"Buy\" A Residency Permit |website=Forbes|date=29 September 2013|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> Golden visas have been especially popular with Chinese nationals, over 100,000 of whom acquired them during the period from 2007 to 2016.<ref>{{cite news|author=CBS/AP|date=12 May 2017|title=Chinese investors spent $24B on \"golden visas\" in U.S. and elsewhere|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/golden-visas-chinese-investors-24-billion-in-u-s-and-elsewhere/|publisher=CBS News}}</ref>\n\n[[Portugal Golden Visa|Portugal's golden visa]] was introduced during the [[Great Recession]] to help attract investment into the country's housing market. By 2016 the country had issued 2,788 golden visas of which 80% had gone to Chinese nationals.<ref name=\"Almeida\">{{cite news|last=Almeida|first=Henrique|date=20 January 2016|title=Chinese Stuck in Portugal's Visa Limbo|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-20/chinese-property-buyers-stuck-in-portugal-s-golden-visa-limbo|work=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nSome countries such as Malta and Cyprus also offer citizenship (\"so-called [[Permanent residency#golden passports|golden passports]]\") to individuals if they invest a certain sum.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gittleson|first=Kim|date=4 June 2014|title=Where is the cheapest place to buy citizenship?|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-27674135|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nThe issuing of so-called \"golden visas\" has sparked controversy in several countries. A lack of demonstrable economic benefits and security concerns have been among the most common criticisms of golden visas. In 2014 the Canadian government suspended their golden visa program. But because of the [[Canada\u2013Qu\u00e9bec Accord relating to Immigration and Temporary Admission of Aliens]] that allows Quebec to maintain its own immigration policy, Quebec maintains its own golden visa program.<ref>{{cite news|last=Yan|first=Sophia|date=25 March 2014|title=Canada kills investor visa popular with Chinese|url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/02/12/news/canada-chinese-immigration/index.html|publisher=CNN}}</ref> The golden visas have been criticized by members of the European Parliament for disfavoring the concept of citizenship<ref>{{cite news|date=22 November 2014|title=Buying their way in|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21633854-schemes-effect-sell-visas-rich-foreigners-come-under-fire-buying-their-way|work=The Economist}}</ref> and in 2014 the [[European Parliament]] approved a [[non-binding resolution]] that an EU passport should not have a \"price tag.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Vi\u00f1a|first=Gonzalo|date=8 April 2016|title=Malta's golden passport scheme draws fresh criticism|url=https://www.ft.com/content/6f98892e-fbf3-11e5-b3f6-11d5706b613b|work=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a study, the EU has won approximately \u20ac25bn over the last 10 years through foreign direct investment programs.<ref>{{cite news|date=24 January 2019|title=Golden visa\u2019 schemes deserve tougher scrutiny|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b6589fdc-1f0b-11e9-b126-46fc3ad87c65|work=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\n== By country ==\nAccording to ''Corpocrat Magazine'' in 2016, the countries with the top-ranked immigrant investor programs in the world were [[Malta]], [[Cyprus]], [[Portugal]], [[Austria]], the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada, [[Antigua and Barbuda]], [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]], Spain, [[Latvia]], [[Monaco]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Ukraine]], [[Grenada]], [[Abkhazia]], [[Saint Lucia]], Australia, Hong Kong, Singapore, UAE and [[Dominica]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://corpocrat.com/2015/10/20/25-immigrant-investor-citizenship-programs-in-the-world/|title=25+ Great Investor Visas in the World \u2013 Corpocrat Magazine|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> However, golden visas represent only a small proportion of new passports. In 2016, 994,800 citizenship applicants were granted across the EU, according to Eurostat, with just 0.1 percent of applications made under investment schemes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9a6eb914-9e23-11e8-85da-eeb7a9ce36e4|title=EU prepares crackdown on \u2018citizenships for sale\u2019|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Dominican passport|Dominica]] implemented [[Dominica citizenship by investment programme|its program]] in 1993 to provide investors the opportunity to gain Dominican citizenship via a contribution to its Economic Diversification Fund or the purchase of an alternatively approved project along with a fee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ciu.govt.kn/st-kitts-nevis-old/citizenship/|title=Citizenship {{!}} Government of St. Kitts & Nevis \u2013 Citizenship By Investment Program|website=www.ciu.govt.kn|access-date=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maltese passport|Malta Individual Investor Programme]],<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://iip.gov.mt/|title=Individual Investor Programme  \u2013 Malta|website=iip.gov.mt|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> which [[Henley & Partners]] was contracted in 2014 by the [[Government of Malta]] to design and implement, is similarly capped at 1,800 applicants. Applicants are subject to a thorough due diligence process which guarantees that only reputable applicants acquire Maltese citizenship. Moreover, applications from countries where international sanctions apply may not be accepted. Applications from a particular country can also be excluded on the basis of a Government policy decision.<ref name=\":1\" /> The minimum investment for this program is $870,000 with a non-refundable contribution of $700,000.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{anchor|Quebec}}\nThe Quebec Immigrant Investor Program is a Canadian program which allows investors who intend to settle in the province of [[Quebec]] to invest money in Canada. The [[Government of Quebec|Quebec government]] said it would accept a maximum of 1,750 applications to the Immigrant Investor Program during the period of 5 to 20 January 2015. Applicants with an intermediate-advanced aptitude in French are not subject to the cap and may apply at any time. The program has been associated with the lack of [[affordable housing in Canada|housing affordability]] in [[Vancouver]].<ref>http://www.richmond-news.com/news/foreign-sales-peak-in-richmond-as-quebec-ramps-up-investor-immigrant-program-1.2300630</ref>\n\nThe United States [[EB-5 visa]] program requires overseas applicants to invest a minimum of anywhere from $500,000 to $1&nbsp;million, depending on the location of the project, and requires at least 10 jobs to be either created or preserved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uscis.gov/eb-5|title=EB-5 Immigrant Investor Program|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> When these criteria are met, the applicant and their family become eligible for a [[Permanent residence (United States)|green card]]. There is an annual cap of 10,000 applications under the EB-5 program.{{cn|date=January 2020}} The US Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) has offered its EB-5 Immigrant Investor Program since 1990. It is designed to encourage foreign investment in infrastructure projects in the US, particularly in Targeted Employment Areas (TEA), high unemployment areas. The funds are channeled through agencies called regional centers, now designated only by the US Department of Homeland Security. The funding opportunities allow the investor to make a sound financial investment and obtain a US \u201cGreen Card.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |last1=Riley |first1=Kim |title=New federal rulemaking makes major changes to EB-5 Immigrant Investor Program |url=https://transportationtodaynews.com/news/14728-new-federal-rulemaking-makes-major-changes-to-eb-5-immigrant-investor-program/ |website=Transportation Today |publisher=Macallan Communications |location=Washington DC |date=26 July 2019}}</ref> One of the more successful examples of the program is Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission's program through the Delaware Valley Regional Center to raise over $200&nbsp;million for completion of a major project on the Pennsylvania Turnpike.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Welitzkin |first1=Paul |title=Chinese investors helping build major US road link |url=http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/us/2014-12/02/content_19013341.htm |work=China Daily (USA) |agency=New Media |date=2 December 2014 |location=New York NY}}</ref>\n\nA large majority of users of such programs are wealthy Chinese seeking legal security and a better quality of life outside of their home country. More than three-quarters of the applicants to Canada's (since canceled) immigrant investor program were Chinese.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaelcole/2014/02/13/canada-slams-door-on-45k-chinese-millionaires-with-end-of-visa-program/|title=Canada Slams Door on 45K Chinese Millionaires With End of Visa Program|last=Cole|first=Michael|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> Money laundering scandals involving banks in Malta and Latvia have made citizenship schemes more contentious by drawing attention to the lack of controls on Russian funds entering EU countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/4f0fb6c4-5f78-11e8-ad91-e01af256df68|title=Malta bank was set up with \u2018criminal proceeds\u2019, say prosecutors|access-date=15 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe UK grants investor visas. As per the official statistics with the [[British Home Office]], as many as 255 Golden Visas were granted in the first half of 2019 alone.<ref>Y-Axis, [https://www.y-axis.com/news/wealthy-people-investing-golden-visa-uk-increasing/ Wealthy people investing in The Golden Visa of the UK increasing] </ref> {{as of|March 2020}}, an individual can apply for the UK Tier 1 (Investor) visa if they wish to invest an amount of \u00a32 million or more in the UK. The applicant must be from outside Switzerland and the European Economic Area to apply for such a visa, along with various other eligibility requirements. With this class of visa, a person can go to the UK for a maximum duration of 3 years and 4 months, with the ability to apply for an extension of 2 more years. The visa holder can apply to settle after 5 years or less; the greater the investment, the shorter the waiting period.<ref name=ukiv>{{cite web | title=Investor visa (Tier 1) | website=GOV.UK | date=7 February 2014 | url=https://www.gov.uk/tier-1-investor | access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Economic citizenship]]\n* [[EB-5 visa]]\n* [[Immigration tariff]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Immigration]]\n[[Category:Foreign direct investment]]\n[[Category:Residency]]\n", "name_user": "GlobalResident", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Some of this information is outdated and many of the terms being used are incorrect. I just added a couple of key points to the text.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immigrant_investor_programs"}
